  <string name="learnings_article0_title">Why On-Device AI Matters: Privacy, Speed, and Control</string>
  <string name="learnings_article0_source">AppsWithLove</string>
  <string name="learnings_article0_description">Running AI on your phone keeps data private, works offline, and costs nothing per request. Here is why that changes things.</string>
  <string name="learnings_article0_date">Apr 2026</string>
  <string name="learnings_article0_read_time">6 min read</string>
  <string name="learnings_article0_body">On-device AI means the model runs directly on your phone. Nothing is sent to a server. This small change has big effects on privacy, speed, and cost.\n\nPrivacy is the biggest win. Your photos, notes, and questions stay on the device. No company sees them. No server logs them. For sensitive things like health data, journal entries, or insurance cards, that matters a lot. It also makes data protection rules like GDPR much easier to follow, because there is no data transfer to worry about in the first place.\n\nSecurity improves too. Cloud AI sends your data over the internet to a server. Every step on that path is a place where someone could read or steal it. On-device AI removes all of those steps. The data never leaves your hand.\n\nSpeed is another clear advantage. There is no network round trip, so the model answers right away. Even on a slow connection, the result feels instant. Modern phone chips can run small models in well under a second.\n\nIt works offline. On a plane, in the mountains, or with bad signal, the AI still works the same way. Cloud AI just stops working in those cases.\n\nCost is zero per request. Cloud AI providers charge for every call, and that adds up fast for an app with many users. On-device models cost nothing to run after the user has downloaded them once.\n\nPersonalization is safer. The model can adapt to your style without sending that data anywhere. Your phone keeps the context to itself.\n\nThe trade-off is size. On-device models are smaller and less powerful than the biggest cloud models. But for most everyday tasks like summaries, translation, simple chat, or pulling fields out of a document, small models are now good enough.</string>

  <string name="learnings_article1_title">What Is LiteRT and How Does It Work</string>
  <string name="learnings_article1_source">Google Developers Blog</string>
  <string name="learnings_article1_description">LiteRT is the engine that runs AI models on your phone. Here is what it does, and how it picks the best chip for the job.</string>
  <string name="learnings_article1_date">Mar 2026</string>
  <string name="learnings_article1_read_time">6 min read</string>
  <string name="learnings_article1_body">LiteRT is a runtime made by Google. A runtime is the piece of software that loads an AI model and runs it on your device. LiteRT used to be called TensorFlow Lite. Google renamed it in 2024 because it now supports models from many sources, not just TensorFlow.\n\nThe job of LiteRT is simple to describe. Take an AI model, and run it as fast as possible on whatever chip is inside the phone.\n\nPhones have different kinds of chips. The CPU is general purpose and handles everyday work. The GPU is good at doing the same kind of math on lots of numbers at once, which is exactly what AI models need. The NPU is a chip made just for AI. It is the fastest option and uses the least battery. LiteRT can use all three.\n\nWhen you run a model, LiteRT picks the best chip for the job automatically. It tries the NPU first. If that is not available, it falls back to the GPU, and then to the CPU. The app does not have to know which one was used.\n\nLiteRT works with models in a special format. The common ones are .tflite and .litertlm. There is a one time conversion step that turns a regular AI model into this format. The conversion shrinks the model and rearranges it so the phone can run it faster, with almost no loss in quality.\n\nFor language models, Google added a layer on top called LiteRT-LM. Chat models need extra work that other models do not. They have to keep track of the conversation, stream words one at a time as they are generated, and manage memory while the model is thinking. LiteRT-LM handles all of that.\n\nLiteRT also runs on more than just Android. The same model file works on iOS, Windows, Mac, Linux, and the web. That is why one model can power apps on many different devices.\n\nIn short, the model is the brain. LiteRT is the engine that makes the brain run well on the hardware it lands on.</string>

  <string name="learnings_article2_title">On-Device LLMs in 2026: What Changed, What\'s Next</string>
  <string name="learnings_article2_source">Edge AI and Vision Alliance</string>
  <string name="learnings_article2_description">The biggest jump in on-device AI did not come from faster chips. It came from smarter models.</string>
  <string name="learnings_article2_date">Feb 2026</string>
  <string name="learnings_article2_read_time">10 min read</string>
  <string name="learnings_article2_body">The biggest jump in on-device AI did not come from faster chips. It came from better ways to build, train, and shrink the models.\n\nThe real bottleneck on a phone is memory speed, not raw compute power. Phones can move about 50 to 90 gigabytes of data per second. A data center GPU can move 30 to 50 times more. This is why models on phones can feel slower even when the chip looks fast on paper. It also explains why 4-bit quantization helps so much. It is not just smaller storage. It also means the phone reads four times less data for every word it generates.\n\nSmall models have caught up fast. Models with under one billion parameters can now handle real tasks. Many labs are pushing this size class. Llama 3.2 ships in 1B and 3B sizes. Gemma 3 goes down to 270M. Phi-4 mini is 3.8B. SmolLM2 covers 135M to 1.7B. Qwen 2.5 starts at 0.5B. The lesson is that training data and method matter more than raw size at this scale. A well-trained small model can beat a much bigger but older one.\n\nThe toolbox to make this work is mature now. Quantization shrinks models with little quality loss. KV cache management lets the model handle long conversations without running out of memory. Speculative decoding can make output 2 to 3 times faster. Pruning removes parts of the model that do little work.\n\nThree trends to watch. First, mixture of experts on phones, where only part of the model runs at a time. Second, test-time compute, where a small model thinks longer to match a bigger one. Third, on-device fine-tuning, where the model learns from you without sending your data anywhere.\n\nThe bottom line is that phones did not turn into data centers. The field just learned to work with what phones already have.</string>

